[1]
Date: Mon 30 Mar 2020
Source: l'Oriente Jour [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://www.lorientlejour.com/article/1212481/un-grand-patron-de-la-microbiologie.html


A great patron of microbiology. Tribute to Jacques F Acar
---------------------------------------------------------
COVID-19 has just claimed an enormously important victim. The world has lost an infectious disease giant, struck down by this apocalyptic virus. It was on his return to France, after a final congress in the United States, that Jacques Acar was hospitalized on [Sat 20 Mar 2020] and became the victim of a rapid evolution of disease which would prevail a week later. After a life entirely dedicated to the fight against microbes, it was a virus that took him.

Jacques Fouad Acar was a great patron of microbiology and infectious diseases in France and around the world. Born in Dakar to Lebanese parents, originally from Deir el-Qamar, he came briefly to Lebanon to finish his secondary studies at the Notre-Dame de Jamhour College before going to settle permanently in France to study medicine. He took his 1st steps in microbiology research at the Institut Pasteur with Professor Yves Chabert and then at Harvard Medical School with Professor Maxwell Finland.

In 1972, he became head of the research unit on antibiotic resistance at the Broussais-Hotel-Dieu faculty of medicine at the Pierre-et-Marie-Curie University in Paris, then head of the clinical microbiology department in affiliated hospitals, notably Saint-Joseph Hospital, Broussais and Hotel-Dieu de Paris. Author of countless publications, he has contributed significantly to the training of a large number of infectious disease specialists and microbiologists around the world, including many from Lebanon. He made it a point of honor to regularly have at least one Lebanese individual in his service!

The staff of the microbiology laboratory listened to his booming voice. Whenever he sometimes commented in a baritone caliber about problems at work, I would hear the staff say in a low voice, "Ah! This is his Lebanese character!" His contributions to knowledge in clinical microbiology and antibiotic resistance alone would constitute a volume!

He insisted on a multinational, pan-European collaboration between France and the Arab and Mediterranean countries, the countries of the Far East and especially with America. He participated in the founding of the European Society of Infectious Diseases and Microbiology (ESCMID), the International Society for Infectious Diseases (ISID), the Alliance for the Prudent Use of Antibiotics (APUA) and the European Group for Antibiotic Resistance.

His obsession with fighting antibiotic resistance persisted after his retirement. He was appointed professor emeritus at Pierre-et-Marie-Curie University, but he continued to work as a consultant to the World Organization for Animal Health (OIE) because he was convinced of the role of abuse of antibiotics in the animal world as the main factor in the selection of resistant germs.

In addition to his genius in microbiology and infectious diseases, Jacques Acar was a man of colossal culture, able to discuss any subject relating to politics and history, theater, painting, and music. Passionate about everything and seeing his superb baritone voice, he took opera lessons and sang in a choir.

Jacques Acar is a loss for the world of microbiology and infectious diseases, a loss difficult to replace. Certainly, no one is irreplaceable. But Jacques Acar will remain in the heart of his family, of his students and of all those who knew him from far or near as a citizen of the world, a family, cultural and scientific light difficult to extinguish.

[byline: Jacques E Mokhbat]

