[2]
Date: Sun 29 Mar 2020
From: Ghassan M Matar <gmatar@aub.edu.lb> [edited]


It is with a heavy heart that I learned about the passing of Professor Jacques Acar on [Thu 26 Mar 2020] following acquisition of COVID-19. Deepest condolences and sympathies are extended to his family and friends during these sad times.

Dr Acar was professor emeritus of clinical microbiology and infectious diseases, Universite Pierre et Marie Curie, Paris, France. He was senior expert at the World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE) Paris, France, and trained at the Pasteur Institute (Prof Y Chabbert) and at Harvard Medical School (Prof M Finland). Since 1972 he served as chief of the research unit on antimicrobial resistance at the Ecole de Medecine "Broussais -Hotel- Dieu" Universite Pierre et Marie Curie, Paris.

Professor Acar was founder member and former president of the ISID (International Society of Infectious diseases) and the ESCMID (European Society of Clinical Microbiology and Infectious Diseases).

I have known Jacques over the past decade as a colleague and a friend through our meetings and conferences. He was highly supportive and friendly all through our encounters. He enjoyed a pleasant personality and interacted in a professional and respectful way with his peers. Our social gatherings over dinners in all these events were pleasant and entertaining and, at the same time, enriching with discussions not only on microbiology and infectious diseases but also on various cultural aspects related to history, arts, music and other. I was deeply saddened by his passing but consoled by his life that he lived abundantly by spreading graciously his enriching knowledge to the world.

The ProMED family and scientific community have lost a great member and leader in Infectious Diseases and Antimicrobial Resistance. Prof Acar will be dearly missed. May his soul rest in peace in God's safe hands.

--
Ghassan M Matar, MSc, PhD
ProMED-MENA Regional Moderator
ProMED-Europe Region Moderator AMR-Network

******
[3]
Date: 29 Mar 2020
From: Norm Stein [edited]


I was saddened to learn that my dear friend Jacques Acar has fallen victim to COVID-19.

Jacques was one of the founders of the ISID and he remained actively involved long after his 15 years of service on the Executive Committee. As ISID's first treasurer he was responsible for the financial well being of the infant organisation from 1983-1988. In 1988 he became the 2nd president of the ISID and further strengthened the organization by virtue of the tremendously successful congress held in Montreal in 1990.

Following his presidency he continued his service as treasurer until 1998 a period which saw the society grow and establish itself as the pre-eminent worldwide infectious disease organisation. Much of this growth was made possible by his tireless efforts in solidifying the financial base of the ISID.

Jacques continued his support of the ISID for an additional 20 years. From 1998 until at least my retirement in 2017 he was a regular contributor the ISID programs and a resource to me in trying to maintain ISID's financial stability. He visited the office regularly and was always available to ISID's program directors and staff.

I shall miss his warmth and genuine concern for all of us.

--
Norm Stein
Former Executive Director, ISID

*****
[4]
Date: 29 March 2020
From: Tim Brewer [edited]


Jacques was a wonderful person who used his skills and knowledge to make the world better. I will miss his keen insight, wise counsel and warm friendship.

--
Tim Brewer
Former Program Director, ISID

[I've known Jacques through the years predominantly at international meetings. He was a strong supporter of ProMED and of the IMED meetings. He was always a bright shining star, loaded with great ideas and pushing them forward into initiatives. He would always come to me with suggestions on how things could be improved and enhanced at ProMED and at the particular meeting. And would encourage networking with his extensive global network, making regular introductions.

His loss will be felt globally as well as personally.

Adding my sincerest condolences to his wife, his family, his friends and colleagues. - Mod.MPP]

I first met Jacques when I was a 4th year medical student. One of my mentors, Sherry Gorbach, reached out to Jacques to arrange an "away" rotation for me at Saint Joseph Hospital in Paris. It was a wonderful experience that I will never forget. Jacques and I reconnected when I joined ProMED in 2002. He has been a source of knowledge and wisdom and a strong supporter of ProMED, and in particular for the International Meeting on Emerging Diseases and Surveillance (IMED), which began in 2007. Jacques helped organize the original meeting and has been on the Scientific Advisory Committee ever since. He was a strong proponent of One Health and worked to engage with OIE in IMED and bring AMR to the forefront.

Jacques called me less than 2 weeks ago, while he was in Providence, RI, to urge that IMED continue despite (and because of) the current pandemic.

I want to extend my sympathy to his wife, his family, his friends and many colleagues. - Mod.LM

